Let $\mathbf{q}$ be the projection of $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}$ onto $\mathbf{w}.$  Then $\mathbf{q}$ is a scalar multiple of $\mathbf{w},$ so
\[\mathbf{q} = c \mathbf{w}\]for some scalar $c.$

Then $\mathbf{q}$ is the projection of $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}$ onto $\mathbf{w}$ if and only if $\mathbf{q} - \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}$ is orthogonal to $\mathbf{w}.$  This vector is given by
\[\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} - \mathbf{q} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} - c \mathbf{w} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 - \frac{2}{3} c \\ 1 - \frac{1}{3} c \end{pmatrix}.\]Thus, we want
\[\begin{pmatrix} 4 - \frac{2}{3} c \\ 1 - \frac{1}{3} c \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{w} = 0.\]We can take $\mathbf{w}$ to be a unit vector, so
\[\begin{pmatrix} 4 - \frac{2}{3} c \\ 1 - \frac{1}{3} c \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} \cos \theta \\ \sin \theta \end{pmatrix} = 0.\]Since $\begin{pmatrix} \cos \theta \\ \sin \theta \end{pmatrix}$ is a unit vector, this reduces to
\[\cos \theta (4 - \frac{2}{3} c) + \sin \theta (1 - \frac{1}{3} c) = 0.\]Substituting $\cos \theta = \frac{9}{10}$ and $\sin \theta = \frac{3}{10},$ we get
\[\frac{27}{25} (4 - \frac{2}{3} c) + \frac{9}{25} (1 - \frac{1}{3} c) = 0.\]Solving for $c,$ we find $c = \boxed{\frac{10}{3}}.$

